Hi Grant, I am following up on our visit to the property on Tuesday. I left=
 the meeting feeling quite confused about several points, and I would be gr=
ateful if you could please clarify the following so I can properly understa=
nd the approach


Hi Grant,

I am following up on our visit to the property on Tuesday. I left the meeti=
ng feeling quite confused about several points, and I would be grateful if =
you could please clarify the following so I can properly understand the app=
roach Tower is taking:

1. Independent expert testing

You indicated that Tower/you will not pay for any expert testing as part of=
 my preparation of the claim, as you said that is what you are already doin=
g. However, I am struggling to understand this position. From my perspectiv=
e, you are preparing the claim from Tower=E2=80=99s side, and I have not be=
en invited to or involved in any of the NZRSC [can you please clarify what =
NZRSC stands for? =E2=80=93 I am sorry, I am not familiar with this acronym=
] assessments or discussions. This does not feel independent or transparent=
 from my side. Attached are the material damage Report & Scope of repair wo=
rks as provided by our technical Building consultant. These are provided to=
 you for your reference and review. I received these from ASURNZ o Friday 5=
th September.

Given the seriousness of the fire, and the chemical involvement (including =
spa chemicals with corrosive chlorides and bromides), I am concerned that c=
ritical risks may be under-assessed. Could you please clarify why Tower wou=
ld not support me in engaging independent engineers, hygienists, or other s=
pecialists to provide an impartial view? We can provide independent swab-te=
sting by a forensic scientist, which tests for chemical contamination which=
 has occurred from the fire. I would need to meet with you to have you prov=
ide context and detail on exactly what chemicals were present and where the=
y were located within the property. I am happy to progress this process fur=
ther with you as soon as possible =E2=80=93 but I will need to establish mo=
re context and detail as to what this potential contamination may be, befor=
e we undertake any testing. We can also share the methodology of the forens=
ic testing with you before we undertake the testing.

Further, I request that I be included in all communications with any assess=
ors and 3rd parties=E2=80=94 including texts, emails, calls, and meetings =
=E2=80=94 and that these be scheduled so I have the opportunity to particip=
ate. This is essential for transparency and to ensure I am properly informe=
d about the basis of decisions being made. I can accommodate this as much a=
s is practically possible. I have kept you fully informed of every step and=
 process that I have undertaken to date when progressing your claim. I unde=
rstand that you have made a privacy request to our claims department =E2=80=
=93 which will provide you with access to all communications regarding your=
 claim. I will forward this request that you have made to a Senior Claims M=
anager =E2=80=93 so that they can respond to your request in a more compreh=
ensive response. This is a Claims Management request =E2=80=93 whereas my f=
ocus is on the structural repairs required for your claim. Please allow to =
forward and escalate this request for you.

2. Structural elements =E2=80=93 linings and framing

You mentioned that, in addition to demolishing and rebuilding the closed de=
ck, your intention is to replace only a couple of structural beams and to r=
ely on methods such as dry-ice blasting and thermal fogging for the bricks.=
 From a technical perspective, this seems inadequate because:

  *   Smoke odour and residue remain even on the first floor =E2=80=94 the =
least affected part of the house =E2=80=94 three months after the fire, sug=
gesting deep penetration.
  *   The fire involved spa chemicals, creating corrosive residues (chlorid=
es, bromides) likely absorbed into linings, timber framing, and fixings. I =
have responded to this as above.
  *   Superficial cleaning, fogging, or painting over residues cannot ensur=
e long-term safety or durability.
  *   Bricks and mortar are porous: once penetrated by smoke and chemical r=
esidues, they can continue to off-gas and deteriorate over time, underminin=
g both habitability and structural performance.
  *
  *   Similarly, timber framing, structural timbers, and plasterboard linin=
gs are fibrous and absorbent. Once smoke and chemical residues penetrate, t=
hey may release odours, compromise air quality, accelerate corrosion of emb=
edded fixings, and create conditions for hidden mould or decay. These risks=
 cannot be fully eliminated by surface cleaning
  *   Your approach appears to focus only on visible damage (e.g. darkened =
beams), while overlooking non-visible but equally serious fire, smoke, and =
water impacts. This is not appropriate, creates significant long-term risks=
, and is not aligned with Tower=E2=80=99s obligation to reinstate the house=
 to an =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D standard.
On that basis, could you clarify how retaining contaminated bricks, timbers=
, and linings meets Tower=E2=80=99s obligation to reinstate the property to=
 a =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D standard? What testing and certification is pla=
nned to ensure these critical services are restored to a safe and =E2=80=9C=
as new=E2=80=9D condition?

3. Roof assessment

You indicated that the roof requires no work. I find this difficult to reco=
ncile with the evidence: [ with respect I said that there was no structural=
 fire damage in the roof space. It could be accepted that there is a faint =
smoke odour in the roof space from any smoke which may have passed through =
this space. We have allowed for replacement of 95 sqm of ceiling insulation=
 to eliminate the possibility of any smoke odours remaining.

  *   Large volumes of black smoke were seen coming out from all sides of t=
he roof during the fire.
  *   A gutter was significantly heat-damaged.
  *   Local reporting even suggested the fire appeared to be in the roof. I=
 have been in the roof space. There is no structural fire damage in the roo=
f space.

If external heat was sufficient to damage guttering, then internal elements=
 such as roof cavity insulation, underlay, battens, fixings, and trusses ma=
y also have been affected. Could you please clarify what inspection methods=
 were used to conclude the roof was undamaged? Were cavity inspections, int=
rusive checks, or residue/chemical tests undertaken? What testing and certi=
fication is planned to ensure these critical services are restored to a saf=
e and =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D condition?

4. Services =E2=80=93 gas, electricity, and water

I understand that you are going to test the gas unit and propose a plan to =
bring it up to new standard, which I appreciate. However, could you also pl=
ease clarify what is planned for the  electricty system, which suffered sig=
nificant and widespread damage and the water distribution system

At present I am unclear how these critical services will be properly tested=
 and reinstated. What testing and certification is planned to ensure these =
critical services are restored to a safe and =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D condi=
tion?

5. Timing and completeness of assessments

I am also confused and  concerned that a repair plan is already being discu=
ssed before full assessments have been completed and before I have seen the=
 NZRSC or other formal reports.

Could you clarify why Tower is progressing toward a repair plan at this sta=
ge rather than awaiting intrusive testing, particularly given the involveme=
nt of corrosive chemicals and deep smoke penetration? What testing and cert=
ification is planned to ensure these critical services are restored to a sa=
fe and =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D condition? And what would be the sequencing=
 of those to inform a realistic plan?

In addition, is it not too risky to wait until after restructuring works to=
 determine whether the house is safe and meets code requirements? That appr=
oach could prolong reinstatement unnecessarily, leaving me at greater disad=
vantage with accommodation costs and delays that are outside my control.

6. Testing and reporting

Could you please confirm:

  *   What tests or assessments have actually been completed so far?
  *   Why, given the involvement of spa chemicals, no intrusive testing has=
 been arranged?
  *   When the NZRSC report and other reports will be made available to me?
  *   What testing and certification is planned to ensure my house restored=
 to a safe and =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D condition? And could you please pro=
vide sequencing and timings.

7. Accommodation support - Claims Manager will answer these questions for y=
ou.



A number of critical assessments remain outstanding =E2=80=94 including tes=
ts for chemical penetration, the roof structure and cavity, and essential s=
ervices such as electricity and water. Until these are properly completed a=
nd confirmed, the house is uninhabitable.

At present, my rental accommodation is being funded under the contents poli=
cy ($30,000 limit). However, with reinstatement not yet underway and key as=
sessments still pending, it is clear this allowance will be insufficient. T=
hese delays are entirely outside my control.

The Fair Insurance Code requires insurers to act fairly and not disadvantag=
e customers through delay. The principle of insurance is to restore the ins=
ured to the pre-loss position. To avoid being placed at a further disadvant=
age, I would like to explore the following options:

  *   Option A: Tower agrees I may take the lead in arranging necessary ass=
essments and reinstatement works, provided all works are to =E2=80=9Cas new=
=E2=80=9D standard, meet current Building Code requirements, and remain wit=
hin the insured sum. Tower would reimburse incurred costs within 15 days of=
 invoice on a monthly basis, ensuring timely progress without administrativ=
e delay.
  *   Option B: Alternatively, Tower confirms that it will continue to cove=
r my accommodation costs until the house is fully restored and habitable, g=
iven that ongoing delays are not of my making.

Could you please confirm which of these approaches Tower is prepared to ado=
pt, so that I am not unfairly disadvantaged by circumstances outside my con=
trol?

8. Privacy Act material =E2=80=93 Claims Manager will answer these question=
s for you.

You previously referred me to information provided under the Privacy Act, w=
hich I could not find. I found those two email but the links I received do =
not open or function. Could you please resend this information, ensuring th=
at the links are accessible, or alternatively provide the documents as dire=
ct PDF/email attachments?

Summary point

At present, I remain unclear how Tower=E2=80=99s proposed approach =E2=80=
=94 which appears to favor superficial cleaning and limited replacement =E2=
=80=94 can reasonably restore my property to a safe, habitable, =E2=80=9Cas=
 new=E2=80=9D standard, particularly given the deep smoke and chemical pene=
tration of bricks, timbers, and linings, the unresolved questions regarding=
 the roof structure and cavity, and the uncertainty around full reinstateme=
nt of essential services such as electricity, water, and gas.

I would greatly appreciate your clarification on each of these points so th=
at I can properly understand how my home will be restored to a safe, habita=
ble, =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D standard,

Kind regards,

Raffaella del Prete

