<div style=3D"border:none;border-top:solid #E1E1E1 1.0pt;padding:3.0pt 0in =
0in 0in">
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><b><span style=3D"font-size:11.0pt;font-family:&quot=
;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif">From:</span></b><span style=3D"font-size:11.0pt;=
font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif"> Raffaella del Prete &lt;raffae=
llanz@icloud.com&gt;
<br>
<b>Sent:</b> Saturday, September 6, 2025 3:04 PM<br>
<b>To:</b> Grant Metson &lt;Grant.Metson@tower.co.nz&gt;<br>
<b>Cc:</b> Claims &lt;Claims@tower.co.nz&gt;<br>
<b>Subject:</b> Request for Clarification - Re: 23 Mays Road - progression =
of claims response. C90306048<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-line-height-alt:.75pt"><span style=3D"f=
ont-size:1.0pt;color:white">Hi Grant, I am following up on our visit to the=
 property on Tuesday. I left the meeting feeling quite confused about sever=
al points, and I would be grateful if
 you could please clarify the following so I can properly understand the ap=
proach<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-line-height-alt:.75pt"><span style=3D"f=
ont-size:1.0pt;color:white"><o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<p>Hi Grant,<o:p></o:p></p>
<p>I am following up on our visit to the property on Tuesday. I left the me=
eting feeling quite confused about several points, and I would be grateful =
if you could please clarify the following so I can properly understand the =
approach Tower is taking:<o:p></o:p></p>
<p><b>1. Independent expert testing</b><o:p></o:p></p>
<p>You indicated that Tower/you will not pay for any expert testing as part=
 of my preparation of the claim, as you said that is what you are already d=
oing. However, I am struggling to understand this position. From my perspec=
tive, you are preparing the claim
 from Tower=E2=80=99s side, and I have not been invited to or involved in a=
ny of the NZRSC
<span style=3D"color:#0070C0">[can you please clarify what NZRSC stands for=
? =E2=80=93 I am sorry, I am not familiar with this acronym]
</span>assessments or discussions. This does not feel independent or transp=
arent from my side.
<span style=3D"color:#0070C0">Attached are the material damage Report &amp;=
 Scope of repair works as provided by our technical Building consultant. Th=
ese are provided to you for your reference and review. I received these fro=
m ASURNZ o Friday 5<sup>th</sup> September.
 &nbsp;</span><o:p></o:p></p>
<p>Given the seriousness of the fire, and the chemical involvement (includi=
ng spa chemicals with corrosive chlorides and bromides), I am concerned tha=
t critical risks may be under-assessed. Could you please clarify why Tower =
would not support me in engaging
 independent engineers, hygienists, or other specialists to provide an impa=
rtial view?
<span style=3D"color:#0070C0">We can provide independent swab-testing by a =
forensic scientist, which tests for chemical contamination which has occurr=
ed from the fire. I would need to meet with you to have you provide context=
 and detail on exactly what chemicals
 were present and where they were located within the property. I am happy t=
o progress this process further with you as soon as possible =E2=80=93 but =
I will need to establish more context and detail as to what this potential =
contamination may be, before we undertake
 any testing. We can also share the methodology of the forensic testing wit=
h you before we undertake the testing. &nbsp;&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p>Further, I request that I be&nbsp;included in all communications with an=
y assessors&nbsp;and 3rd parties=E2=80=94 including texts, emails, calls, a=
nd meetings =E2=80=94 and that these be scheduled so I have the opportunity=
 to participate. This is essential for transparency and to
 ensure I am properly informed about the basis of decisions being made. <sp=
an style=3D"color:#0070C0">
I can accommodate this as much as is practically possible. I have kept you =
fully informed of every step and process that I have undertaken to date whe=
n progressing your claim. I understand that you have made a privacy request=
 to our claims department =E2=80=93 which
 will provide you with access to all communications regarding your claim. I=
 will forward this request that you have made to a
<u>Senior Claims Manager</u> =E2=80=93 so that they can respond to your req=
uest in a more comprehensive response. This is a Claims Management request =
=E2=80=93 whereas my focus is on the structural repairs required for your c=
laim. Please allow to forward and escalate this
 request for you. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p><b>2. Structural elements =E2=80=93 linings and framing</b><o:p></o:p></=
p>
<p>You mentioned that, in addition to demolishing and rebuilding the closed=
 deck, your intention is to replace only a couple of structural beams and t=
o rely on methods such as dry-ice blasting and thermal fogging for the bric=
ks. From a technical perspective,
 this seems inadequate because:<o:p></o:p></p>
<div>
<ul type=3D"disc">
<li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-=
alt:auto;mso-list:l5 level1 lfo1">
Smoke odour and residue remain even on the first floor =E2=80=94 the least =
affected part of the house =E2=80=94 three months after the fire, suggestin=
g deep penetration.
<o:p></o:p></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;ms=
o-margin-bottom-alt:auto;mso-list:l5 level1 lfo1">
The fire involved spa chemicals, creating corrosive residues (chlorides, br=
omides) likely absorbed into linings, timber framing, and fixings.
<span style=3D"color:#0070C0">I have responded to this as above.</span><o:p=
></o:p></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-ma=
rgin-bottom-alt:auto;mso-list:l5 level1 lfo1">
Superficial cleaning, fogging, or painting over residues cannot ensure long=
-term safety or durability.<o:p></o:p></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D=
"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto;mso-list:l5 level1 lfo1=
">
Bricks and mortar are porous: once penetrated by smoke and chemical residue=
s, they can continue to off-gas and deteriorate over time, undermining both=
 habitability and structural performance.<o:p></o:p></li><li class=3D"MsoNo=
rmal" style=3D"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto;mso-list:=
l5 level1 lfo1">
<o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-margin-top-alt:a=
uto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto;mso-list:l5 level1 lfo1">
Similarly, timber framing, structural timbers, and plasterboard linings are=
 fibrous and absorbent. Once smoke and chemical residues penetrate, they ma=
y release odours, compromise air quality, accelerate corrosion of embedded =
fixings, and create conditions for
 hidden mould or decay. These risks cannot be fully eliminated by surface c=
leaning<o:p></o:p></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-margin-top-alt:=
auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto;mso-list:l5 level1 lfo1">
Your approach appears to focus only on visible damage (e.g. darkened beams)=
, while overlooking non-visible but equally serious fire, smoke, and water =
impacts. This is not appropriate, creates significant long-term risks, and =
is not aligned with Tower=E2=80=99s obligation
 to reinstate the house to an =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D standard.<o:p></o:p>=
</li></ul>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal">On that basis, could you clarify how retaining conta=
minated bricks, timbers, and linings meets Tower=E2=80=99s obligation to re=
instate the property to a =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D standard? What testing a=
nd certification is planned to ensure these critical services
 are restored to a safe and =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D condition?<o:p></o:p><=
/p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><b>3. Roof assessment</b><o:p></o:p></p>
</div>
<p>You indicated that the roof requires no work. I find this difficult to r=
econcile with the evidence<span style=3D"color:#0070C0">: [ with respect I =
said that there was no structural fire damage in the roof space. It could b=
e accepted that there is a faint smoke
 odour in the roof space from any smoke which may have passed through this =
space. We have allowed for replacement of 95 sqm of ceiling insulation to e=
liminate the possibility of any smoke odours remaining.</span> &nbsp;<o:p><=
/o:p></p>
<ul type=3D"disc">
<li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-=
alt:auto;mso-list:l6 level1 lfo2">
Large volumes of black smoke were seen coming out from all sides of the roo=
f during the fire.<o:p></o:p></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-marg=
in-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto;mso-list:l6 level1 lfo2">
A gutter was significantly heat-damaged.<o:p></o:p></li><li class=3D"MsoNor=
mal" style=3D"color:#0070C0;mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:a=
uto;mso-list:l6 level1 lfo2">
<span style=3D"color:windowtext">Local reporting even suggested the fire ap=
peared to be in the roof. I have been in the roof space.
</span>There is no structural fire damage in the roof space. <o:p></o:p></l=
i></ul>
<p>If external heat was sufficient to damage guttering, then internal eleme=
nts such as roof cavity insulation, underlay, battens, fixings, and trusses=
 may also have been affected. Could you please clarify what inspection meth=
ods were used to conclude the roof
 was undamaged? Were cavity inspections, intrusive checks, or residue/chemi=
cal tests undertaken? What testing and certification is planned to ensure t=
hese critical services are restored to a safe and =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D =
condition?<o:p></o:p></p>
<p><b>4. Services =E2=80=93 gas, electricity, and water</b><o:p></o:p></p>
<p>I understand that you are going to test the gas unit and propose a plan =
to bring it up to new standard, which I appreciate. However, could you also=
 please clarify what is planned for the &nbsp;electricty system, which suff=
ered significant and widespread damage
 and the water distribution system<o:p></o:p></p>
<p>At present I am unclear how these critical services will be properly tes=
ted and reinstated. What testing and certification is planned to ensure the=
se critical services are restored to a safe and =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D co=
ndition?<o:p></o:p></p>
<p><b>5. Timing and completeness of assessments</b><o:p></o:p></p>
<p>I am also confused and &nbsp;concerned that a repair plan is already bei=
ng discussed before full assessments have been completed and before I have =
seen the NZRSC or other formal reports.<o:p></o:p></p>
<p>Could you clarify why Tower is progressing toward a repair plan at this =
stage rather than awaiting intrusive testing, particularly given the involv=
ement of corrosive chemicals and deep smoke penetration? What testing and c=
ertification is planned to ensure
 these critical services are restored to a safe and =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=
=9D condition? And what would be the sequencing of those to inform a realis=
tic plan?<o:p></o:p></p>
<p>In addition, is it not too risky to wait until after restructuring works=
 to determine whether the house is safe and meets code requirements? That a=
pproach could prolong reinstatement unnecessarily, leaving me at greater di=
sadvantage with accommodation costs
 and delays that are outside my control.&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></p>
<p><b>6. Testing and reporting</b><o:p></o:p></p>
<p>Could you please confirm:<o:p></o:p></p>
<ul type=3D"disc">
<li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-=
alt:auto;mso-list:l3 level1 lfo3">
What tests or assessments have actually been completed so far?<o:p></o:p></=
li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bott=
om-alt:auto;mso-list:l3 level1 lfo3">
Why, given the involvement of spa chemicals, no intrusive testing has been =
arranged?<o:p></o:p></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-margin-top-al=
t:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto;mso-list:l3 level1 lfo3">
When the NZRSC report and other reports will be made available to me?<o:p><=
/o:p></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-marg=
in-bottom-alt:auto;mso-list:l3 level1 lfo3">
What testing and certification is planned to ensure my house restored to a =
safe and =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D condition? And could you please provide s=
equencing and timings.<o:p></o:p></li></ul>
<p><b>7. Accommodation support - </b><span style=3D"color:#0070C0">Claims M=
anager will answer these questions for you.
<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>
<p>A number of critical assessments remain outstanding =E2=80=94 including =
tests for chemical penetration, the roof structure and cavity, and essentia=
l services such as electricity and water. Until these are properly complete=
d and confirmed, the house is uninhabitable.<o:p></o:p></p>
<p>At present, my rental accommodation is being funded under the contents p=
olicy ($30,000 limit). However, with reinstatement not yet underway and key=
 assessments still pending, it is clear this allowance will be insufficient=
. These delays are entirely outside
 my control.<o:p></o:p></p>
<p>The Fair Insurance Code requires insurers to act fairly and not disadvan=
tage customers through delay. The principle of insurance is to restore the =
insured to the pre-loss position. To avoid being placed at a further disadv=
antage, I would like to explore
 the following options:<o:p></o:p></p>
<ul type=3D"disc">
<li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-=
alt:auto;mso-list:l9 level1 lfo4">
Option A: Tower agrees I may take the lead in arranging necessary assessmen=
ts and reinstatement works, provided all works are to =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=
=9D standard, meet current Building Code requirements, and remain within th=
e insured sum. Tower would reimburse incurred costs
 within 15 days of invoice on a monthly basis, ensuring timely progress wit=
hout administrative delay.<o:p></o:p></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"=
mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto;mso-list:l9 level1 lfo4">
Option B: Alternatively, Tower confirms that it will continue to cover my a=
ccommodation costs until the house is fully restored and habitable, given t=
hat ongoing delays are not of my making.<o:p></o:p></li></ul>
<p>Could you please confirm which of these approaches Tower is prepared to =
adopt, so that I am not unfairly disadvantaged by circumstances outside my =
control?<o:p></o:p></p>
<p><b>8. Privacy Act material =E2=80=93 </b><span style=3D"color:#0070C0">C=
laims Manager will answer these questions for you.
<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p>You previously referred me to information provided under the Privacy Act=
, which I could not find. I found those two email but the links I received =
do not open or function. Could you please resend this information, ensuring=
 that the links are accessible,
 or alternatively provide the documents as direct PDF/email attachments?<o:=
p></o:p></p>
<p><b>Summary point</b><o:p></o:p></p>
<p>At present, I remain unclear how Tower=E2=80=99s proposed approach =E2=
=80=94 which appears to favor superficial cleaning and limited replacement =
=E2=80=94 can reasonably restore my property to a safe, habitable, =E2=80=
=9Cas new=E2=80=9D standard, particularly given the deep smoke and chemical
 penetration of bricks, timbers, and linings, the unresolved questions rega=
rding the roof structure and cavity, and the uncertainty around full reinst=
atement of essential services such as electricity, water, and gas.<o:p></o:=
p></p>
<p>I would greatly appreciate your clarification on each of these points so=
 that I can properly understand how my home will be restored to a safe, hab=
itable, =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D standard,<o:p></o:p></p>
<p>Kind regards,<o:p></o:p></p>
<p>Raffaella del Prete<o:p></o:p></p>
